<p>In Lua, there are many ways to generate error messages:</p>  <pre class="lang-none prettyprint-override"><code>[soniex2@soniex-pc ~]$ lua Lua 5.3.1  Copyright (C) 1994-2015 Lua.org, PUC-Rio &gt; hi! stdin:1: syntax error near '!' &gt; :: &gt;&gt; :: stdin:2: &lt;name&gt; expected near '::' &gt; ~ stdin:1: unexpected symbol near '~' &gt; pcall() stdin:1: bad argument #1 to 'pcall' (value expected) stack traceback:     [C]: in function 'pcall'     stdin:1: in main chunk     [C]: in ? &gt; table.insert() stdin:1: bad argument #1 to 'insert' (table expected, got no value) stack traceback:     [C]: in function 'table.insert'     stdin:1: in main chunk     [C]: in ? </code></pre>  <p>And as you can see, all the error messages are in all-lowercase.</p>  <p>Why is this?</p>  <p>(This isn't exclusive to Lua, but there wasn't/isn't a tag for it.)</p>